The Composite Field of \Bbbk _{1} with \Bbbk _{2} is the smallest field subfield denoted \Bbbk _{1}\Bbbk _{2} of \mathbb {L} containing both \Bbbk _{1} and \Bbbk _{2}.

Let x,y\in  R be arbitrary. Then we can write them out as
x=\sum _{i,j}c_{i,j}\alpha _{i}\beta _{j}
and
y=\sum _{i,j}d_{i,j}\alpha _{i}\beta _{j}
for some c_{i,j}\in \mathbb {F} and d_{i,j}\in \mathbb {F}.

Since \Bbbk _{1} is closed under multiplication, and \{\alpha _{i}\}_{i\in  I} is an \mathbb {F}-basis for \Bbbk _{1}, we have for any i_{1},i_{2}\in  I,
\alpha _{i_{1}}\alpha _{i_{2}}=\sum _{i}a_{i}\alpha _{i}
for some coefficients a_{i}\in \mathbb {F}. Similarly,
\beta _{j_{1}}\beta _{j_{2}}=\sum _{j}b_{j}\beta _{j}
for some b_{j}\in \mathbb {F}. Then
\alpha _{i_{1}}\alpha _{i_{2}}\beta _{j_{1}}\beta _{j_{2}}=\sum _{i,j}a_{i}b_{j}\alpha _{i}\beta _{j}\in  R.
Since the product xy is a linear combination of elements of this form, it follows that R is a subring of \mathbb {L}.

Let R be a Ring. Let x\neq 0 be a nonzero element of R. We say x is:

a Left Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and xy=0;

a Right Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq  0 and yx=0;

a (Two Sided) Zero Divisor if there exists a y\in  R such that y\neq 0 and xy=0 and yx=0.
The way to remember left and right zero divisors is which side x appears.

Consider \varepsilon \in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{2}(\mathbb {C}) defined as
\varepsilon =\begin {pmatrix}0 & 1\\ 0 & 0\end {pmatrix}
We see that \varepsilon ^{2}=0. Hence \varepsilon  is a zero divisor.

(1) We can extend this to as many unknowns as we want, writing R[x_{1},…,x_{n}] or even R[x_{1},…,x_{n},…] for infinitely many unknowns. Then the sums make use of Multi-index notation. For example, for R[x,y] we have
p(x,y)=\sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha _{1}}y^{\alpha _{2}}
and so on. In fact, Dummit and Foote Abstract Algebra define (Section 9.1) R[x_{1},…,x_{n}]=R[x_{1},…,x_{n-1}][x_{n}].

Let R be a nonempty Commutative Ring. Let x_{1}, …, x_{m} be formal variables. Let
p(x) = \sum ^{n}_{|\alpha |=0}a_{\alpha }x^{\alpha }
be a formal polynomial, i.e., p\in  R[x_{1},…,x_{m}] with some \alpha  having |\alpha |=n being such that a_{\alpha }\neq 0. Then we define the Degree of p to be the non-negative integer \deg (p) equal to n.

An Integral domain R is called a Unique Factorization Domain (or UFD for short, older texts say R is Factorial) if

Nonzero elements have a Factorization: For every nonzero element a\in R^{*} there exists a factorization
a=u\prod ^{N}_{j=1}p_{j}^{n_{j}}
where u\in R^{\times } is a unit, p_{j}\in  R are distinct irreducitlbe elements, and n_{j}\in \mathbb {N} are positive integers; and

Factorizations are unique: For every nonzero element a\in R^{*} if there are two factorizations
a=u\prod ^{N}_{j=1}p_{j}^{n_{j}}
and
a=v\prod ^{N'}_{j=1}q_{j}^{m_{j}}
then N=N' and there exists a permutation \sigma \in  S_{N} such that u_{j}p_{j}=q_{\sigma (j)} and n_{j}=m_{\sigma (j)} for units u_{j}\in R^{\times }.

