Let V be a finite-dimensional real vector space with a well-defined notion of a dot product. Let B be an orthogonal basis of V. We call B an Orthonormal Basis of V if for all f\in  B we also have f\cdot  f=1. In other words, we have for all f_{i},f_{j}\in  B,
f_{i}\cdot  f_{j}=\delta _{i,j}
where \delta _{i,j} is the Kronecker delta.

Let V be a finite-dimensional real vector space. Let B=(f_{1},…,f_{n}) be an Ordered Basis of V. Then we call the n coefficients \lambda _{1},…,\lambda _{n}\in \mathbb {R} such that
v = \lambda _{1}f_{1}+…+\lambda _{n}f_{n}
are called the Coordinates of v relative to B. We can write this down as a column vector:
[v]_{B} = \begin {pmatrix}\lambda _{1}\\\vdots \\\lambda _{n}\end {pmatrix}
for the coordinates of v relative of B.

Let V be a finite-dimensional real vector space. Let u,v\in  V be vectors. Assume u\neq \vec {0}. We define the Projection of v along the u direction to be the vector
\mathrm {Proj}_{u}(v)=\frac {u\cdot  v}{u\cdot  u}u=(\widehat {u}\cdot  v)\widehat {u}
where \widehat {u}=u/\sqrt {u\cdot  u} is the unit vector in the u-direction.

This is a linear transformation since \mathop {	extrm {id}}
